  "title": "Line and Plane",
  "concepts": [
    {
      "title": "Intersection of a Line and Plane",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Intersection of a line and a plane</strong></h3><p>To find the point of intersection of the line $\\frac{x-{{x}_{1}}}{l}=\\frac{y-{{y}_{1}}}{m}=\\frac{z-{{z}_{1}}}{n}$ and the plane $ax+by+cz+d=0$</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"257\" height=\"173\">&nbsp;</p><p>The coordinates of any point on the line</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} {} &amp; \\frac{\\text{x}-{{\\text{x}}_{1}}}{\\text{l}}=\\frac{\\text{y}-{{\\text{y}}_{1}}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ m}}=\\frac{\\text{z}-{{\\text{z}}_{1}}}{\\text{n}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ are }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ given }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ by }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ } \\\\ {} &amp; \\frac{\\text{x}-{{\\text{x}}_{1}}}{\\text{l}}=\\frac{\\text{y}-{{\\text{y}}_{1}}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ m}}=\\frac{\\text{z}-{{\\text{z}}_{1}}}{\\text{n}}=\\text{r }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ (say)} \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ } \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>or $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{lr},{{\\text{y}}_{1}}+\\text{mr},{{\\text{z}}_{1}}+\\text{nr} \\right)$ …(i)</p><p>If it lies on the plane $ax+by+cz+d=0$, then</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} {} &amp; \\text{a}\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{lr} \\right)+\\text{b}\\left( {{\\text{y}}_{1}}+\\text{mr} \\right)+\\text{c}\\left( {{\\text{z}}_{1}}+\\text{nr} \\right)+\\text{d}=0 \\\\ \\Rightarrow &amp; ~\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\left( \\text{a}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{b}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}+\\text{c}{{\\text{z}}_{1}}+\\text{d} \\right)+\\text{r}\\left( \\text{al}+\\text{bm}+\\text{cn} \\right)=0 \\\\ \\Rightarrow &amp; ~\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ r}=-\\frac{\\left( \\text{a}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{b}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}+c{{z}_{1}}+\\text{d} \\right)}{\\text{al}+\\text{bm}+\\text{cn}} \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>Substituting the value of $\\text{r}$ in(i), we obtain the coordinates of the required point of intersection.</p><p><strong>Q) Find the point of intersection of the line $\\frac{x-1}{2}=\\frac{y-2}{-3}=\\frac{z+5}{4}$ and the plane $2x+4y-z=3$&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Any point on the line $\\frac{\\text{x}-1}{2}=\\frac{\\text{y}-2}{-3}=\\frac{\\text{z}+5}{4}$ can be taken as</p><p>$\\left( 1+2\\lambda ,2-3\\lambda ,-5+4\\lambda \\right)$ …(i)</p><p>If this point lies on the plane $2x+4y-z=3$, then</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} {} &amp; 2\\left( 1+2\\lambda \\right)+4\\left( 2-3\\lambda \\right)-\\left( -5+4\\lambda \\right) &amp; =3 &amp; {} \\\\ \\Rightarrow &amp; 2+4\\lambda +8-12\\lambda +5-4\\lambda &amp; =3 &amp; {} \\\\ \\Rightarrow &amp; 15-12\\lambda &amp; =3 &amp; {} \\\\ \\Rightarrow &amp; \\lambda &amp; =1 &amp; {} \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ From (i), point of intersection is $\\left( 1+2,2-3,-5+4 \\right)$ i.e. $\\left( 3,-1,-1 \\right)$.</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0ddd4c03b9dcaf1afecef"
    },
    {
      "title": "Angle between Line and Plane",
      "conceptBody": "<h3>Angle between a line and a plane</h3><p>Let the line be $\\vec{r}=\\vec{a}+\\lambda \\vec{b}$ and the plane be $\\vec{r}\\cdot \\vec{n}=d$. If $\\theta $ is the angle between them then</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} {} &amp; \\text{cos}\\left( {{90}^{\\circ }}-\\theta \\right)=\\frac{\\vec{b}\\cdot \\vec{n}}{\\left| {\\vec{b}} \\right|\\left| {\\vec{n}} \\right|} \\\\ \\Rightarrow &amp; ~\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ sin}\\theta =\\frac{\\vec{b}\\cdot \\vec{n}}{\\left| {\\vec{b}} \\right|\\left| {\\vec{n}} \\right|} \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"212\" height=\"171\">&nbsp;</p><p>In Cartesian form, if the plane is $\\text{ax}+\\text{by}+\\text{cz}+\\text{d}=0$ and line</p><p>is $\\frac{\\text{x}-{{\\text{x}}_{1}}}{\\text{l}}=\\frac{\\text{y}-{{\\text{y}}_{1}}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ m}}=\\frac{\\text{z}-{{\\text{z}}_{1}}}{\\text{n}}$ then</p><p>$\\text{sin}\\theta =\\frac{\\sqrt{\\text{al}+\\text{bm}+\\text{cn}}}{\\sqrt{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}+{{\\text{b}}^{2}}+{{\\text{c}}^{2}}}\\sqrt{{{1}^{2}}+{{\\text{m}}^{2}}+{{\\text{n}}^{2}}}}$</p><p>So, the condition that line is parallel to the plane is $\\vec{b}.\\vec{n}=0$ or $al+bm+cn=0$ and the condition of perpendicular is $\\vec{b}=\\lambda \\vec{n}$ or $\\frac{\\text{l}}{\\text{a}}=\\frac{\\text{m}}{\\text{b}}=\\frac{\\text{n}}{\\text{c}}$.</p>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0ddd4c03b9dcaf1afecf0"
    },
    {
      "title": "Distance of a point from a Plane Measured Parallel to Line",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Distance of a point from a Plane Measured Parallel to Line</strong></h3><p><strong>Q) Find the distance between the point with position vector $-\\overset{}{\\mathop{i}}\\,-5\\overset{}{\\mathop{j}}\\,-10\\overset{}{\\mathop{k}}\\,$ and the point of intersection of the line $\\frac{x-2}{3}=\\frac{y+1}{4}=\\frac{z-2}{12}$ with the plane $x-y+z=5$.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>The coordinates of any point on the line</p><p>$\\frac{\\text{x}-2}{3}=\\frac{\\text{y}+1}{4}=\\frac{\\text{z}-2}{12}=\\text{r}\\left( \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ say }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ } \\right)\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ are }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\left( 3\\text{r}+2,4\\text{r}-1,12\\text{r}+2 \\right)$ …(i)</p><p>If it lies on the plane $\\text{x}-\\text{y}+\\text{z}=5$, then</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} 3\\text{r}+2-4\\text{r}+1+12\\text{r}+2=5 &amp; {} &amp; \\Rightarrow 11\\text{r}=0 \\\\ {} &amp; {} &amp; \\Rightarrow \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ r}=0. \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>Putting $\\text{r}=0$ in (i), we obtain $\\left( 2,-1,2 \\right)$ as the coordinates of the point of intersection of the given line and plane.</p><p>Required distance $=$ distance between $\\left( -1,-5,-10 \\right)$ and $\\left( 2,-1,2 \\right)$</p><p>$=\\sqrt{{{(2+1)}^{2}}+{{(-1+5)}^{2}}+{{(2+10)}^{2}}}=13$</p>",
      "position": 2,
      "qcConcept": "66a0ddd5c03b9dcaf1afecf1"
    },
    {
      "title": "Line to Lie in a Plane",
      "conceptBody": "<h3>Condition for line to lie in a plane</h3><ol><li><strong>Vector Form : </strong>If the line $\\vec{r}=\\vec{a}+\\lambda \\vec{b}$ lies in the plane $\\vec{r}\\cdot \\vec{n}=d$, then (i) $\\vec{b}\\cdot \\vec{n}=0$ and (ii) $\\vec{a}\\cdot \\vec{n}=d$.</li><li><strong>Cartesian Form : </strong>If the line $\\frac{\\text{x}-{{\\text{x}}_{1}}}{\\text{l}}=\\frac{\\text{y}-{{\\text{y}}_{1}}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ m}}=\\frac{\\text{z}-{{\\text{z}}_{1}}}{\\text{n}}$ lies in the plane $\\text{ax}+\\text{by}+\\text{cz}+\\text{d}=0$ then (i) $\\text{a}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{b}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}+\\text{c}{{\\text{z}}_{1}}+{{\\text{d}}_{1}}=0$ and (ii) $\\text{al}+\\text{bm}+\\text{cn}=0$.</li></ol><p><strong>Q) Show that the line $\\vec{r}=\\left( \\overset{}{\\mathop{i}}\\,+\\overset{}{\\mathop{j}}\\, \\right)+\\lambda \\left( 2\\overset{}{\\mathop{i}}\\,+\\overset{}{\\mathop{j}}\\,+4\\overset{}{\\mathop{k}}\\, \\right)$ lies on the plane $\\vec{r}\\cdot \\left( \\overset{}{\\mathop{i}}\\,+2\\overset{}{\\mathop{j}}\\,-\\overset{}{\\mathop{k}}\\, \\right)=3$.</strong></p><p><strong>Solution :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>If the line</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{l}} \\vec{r}=\\left( \\overset{}{\\mathop{\\text{i}}}\\,+\\overset{}{\\mathop{\\text{j}}}\\, \\right)+\\lambda \\left( 2\\overset{}{\\mathop{\\text{i}}}\\,+\\overset{}{\\mathop{\\text{j}}}\\,+4\\overset{}{\\mathop{\\text{k}}}\\, \\right) \\text{ lies } \\text{ on } \\text{ the } \\text{ plane } &nbsp;&amp; {} \\\\ \\vec{r}\\cdot \\left( \\overset{}{\\mathop{\\text{i}}}\\,+2\\overset{}{\\mathop{\\text{j}}}\\,-\\overset{}{\\mathop{\\text{k}}}\\, \\right)=3 \\text{ then } \\text{ line } \\text{ must } \\text{ satisfy } \\text{ the } \\text{ equation } \\text{ of } \\text{ plane} &amp; &nbsp; \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>i.e. $\\left[ \\left( \\overset{}{\\mathop{i}}\\,+\\overset{}{\\mathop{j}}\\, \\right)+\\lambda \\left( 2\\overset{}{\\mathop{i}}\\,+\\overset{}{\\mathop{j}}\\,+4\\overset{}{\\mathop{k}}\\, \\right) \\right]\\cdot \\left( \\overset{}{\\mathop{i}}\\,+2\\overset{}{\\mathop{j}}\\,-\\overset{}{\\mathop{k}}\\, \\right)=3$</p><p>$\\Rightarrow &nbsp;\\left( 1+2 \\right)+\\lambda \\left( 2+2-4 \\right)=3 \\Rightarrow &nbsp;3=3 &nbsp;\\text{ which } \\text{ is } \\text{ true}\\text{. }$</p>",
      "position": 3,
      "qcConcept": "66a0ddd5c03b9dcaf1afecf2"
    },
    {
      "title": "Coplanarity of Lines",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Condition of coplanarity of two lines and equation of the plane containing them</strong></h3><p><strong>Vector Form&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Let $\\vec{r}=\\vec{a}+\\lambda {{\\vec{m}}_{1}}$ and $\\vec{r}=\\vec{b}+\\mu {{\\vec{m}}_{2}}$ be two coplanar lines.</p><p>Then, the plane containing them is parallel to $\\vec{b}-\\vec{a},{{\\vec{m}}_{1}}$ and ${{\\vec{m}}_{2}}$. Therefore $\\vec{b}-\\vec{a},{{\\vec{m}}_{1}}$ and ${{\\vec{m}}_{2}}$ are coplanar.</p><p>$\\therefore \\left[ \\begin{array}{*{35}{l}} \\bar{r}-\\bar{b} &amp; {{\\text{m}}_{1}} &amp; \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{2}} \\\\ \\end{array} \\right]=0$ or $\\left[ \\begin{array}{*{35}{l}} \\bar{r}-\\bar{a} &amp; {{\\text{m}}_{1}} &amp; \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{2}} \\\\ \\end{array} \\right]=0$</p><p><strong>Cartesian Form&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Let $\\text{ }\\frac{\\text{x}-{{\\text{x}}_{1}}}{{{\\text{a}}_{1}}}=\\frac{\\text{y}-{{\\text{y}}_{1}}}{\\text{ }{{\\text{b}}_{1}}}=\\frac{\\text{z}-{{\\text{z}}_{1}}}{{{\\text{c}}_{1}}}$ and</p><p>$\\frac{\\text{x}-{{\\text{x}}_{2}}}{{{\\text{a}}_{2}}}=\\frac{\\text{y}-{{\\text{y}}_{2}}}{\\text{ }{{\\text{b}}_{2}}}=\\frac{\\text{z}-{{\\text{z}}_{2}}}{{{\\text{c}}_{2}}}\\text{ be } \\text{ two } \\text{ coplanar } \\text{ lines } \\text{ then }$</p><p>$\\vec{a}={{\\text{x}}_{1}}\\overset{}{\\hat{\\text{i}}}\\,+{{\\text{y}}_{1}}\\overset{}{\\hat{\\text{j}}}\\,+{{\\text{z}}_{1}}\\overset{}{\\hat{\\text{k}}}\\,$</p><p>$\\vec{b}=x_{2} \\tilde{i}+y_{2} \\tilde{j}+z_{2} \\tilde{k}$</p><p>${{\\vec{m}}_{1}}={{\\text{a}}_{1}}\\overset{}{\\hat{\\text{i}}}\\,+{{\\text{b}}_{1}}\\overset{}{\\hat{\\text{j}}}\\,+{{\\text{c}}_{1}}\\overset{}{\\hat{\\text{k}}}\\,\\text{ and }{{\\vec{m}}_{2}}={{\\text{a}}_{2}}\\overset{}{\\hat{\\text{i}}}\\,+{{\\text{b}}_{2}}\\overset{}{\\hat{\\text{j}}}\\,+{{\\text{c}}_{2}}\\overset{}{\\hat{\\text{k}}}\\,$</p><p>$\\therefore$ condition of complanarity</p><p>$\\left[ \\begin{array}{*{35}{l}} \\vec{b}-\\vec{a} &amp; {{{\\vec{m}}}_{1}} &amp; {{{\\vec{m}}}_{2}} \\\\ \\end{array} \\right]=0$</p><p>Equation of plane</p><p>$\\begin{array}{l} {} &amp; \\left[ \\begin{array}{*{35}{l}} \\vec{r}-\\vec{a} &amp; {{{\\vec{m}}}_{1}} &amp; {{{\\vec{m}}}_{2}} \\\\ \\end{array} \\right]=0 \\\\ \\Rightarrow &amp; \\left| \\begin{matrix} x-{{x}_{1}} &amp; y-{{y}_{1}} &amp; z-{{z}_{1}} \\\\ {{a}_{1}} &amp; {{b}_{1}} &amp; {{c}_{1}} \\\\ {{a}_{2}} &amp; {{b}_{2}} &amp; {{c}_{2}} \\\\ \\end{matrix} \\right|=0 \\\\ \\text{or} &amp;\\left[ \\begin{array}{*{35}{l}} \\vec{r}-\\vec{b} &amp; {{{\\vec{m}}}_{1}} &amp; {{{\\vec{m}}}_{2}} \\\\ \\end{array} \\right]=0 \\\\ \\Rightarrow &amp; \\left| \\begin{matrix} \\text{x}-{{\\text{x}}_{2}} &amp; \\text{y}-{{\\text{y}}_{2}} &amp; \\text{z}-{{\\text{z}}_{2}} \\\\ {{\\text{a}}_{1}} &amp;{{\\text{b}}_{1}} &amp; {{\\text{c}}_{1}} \\\\ {{\\text{a}}_{2}} &amp;{{\\text{b}}_{2}} &amp; {{\\text{c}}_{2}} \\\\ \\end{matrix} \\right|=0 \\\\ \\end{array}$</p>",
      "position": 4,
      "qcConcept": "66a0ddd5c03b9dcaf1afecf3"
    }
  ],
